english:
  title: Stele Inscription for Lord Seongyeong, Grand Defender of the State, of the Byeon Clan in the Glorious Ming's Joseon Kingdom
  author: Byeon Gyeyiang
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the sixteenth year of Yongle, in the year of Muwu, on the fifth day of the second spring month, the Grand Defender of State, Lord Seongyeong, passed from illness at the tender age of fourteen. The royal attendants conveyed the king's words, saying: "Lord Seongyeong has departed from us. Not only was his life cut short, but he left no heir. How can my sorrow find end? Let the court historians erect a stele at his tomb that it may endure forever, and thereby offer some solace to his spirit in the nine depths below, and perhaps ease my endless grief." I, your humble servant Gyeyiang, received this command with trembling reverence.

    Upon careful examination, Lord Seongyeong—born of the same mother as the Crown Prince, fourth among the brothers—was born on the day Imyin in the seventh month of autumn in the year Eul-yu. His form was dignified and fair, his intelligence extraordinary. In the frivolous games of childhood, he showed neither preference nor attachment, and thus earned the profound affection of both Their Majesties. At eight years of age he commenced his studies, advancing daily without the slightest negligence. Skilled in archery, his arrows flew a hundred and fifty paces, earning the admiration of accomplished men in their prime. In filial piety toward his parents and respect toward his brothers, he embodied perfect conduct, bearing himself as a man of mature years. His Highness cherished him ever more deeply, keeping him always at his side through all hours of rest and meals. In the first month of the year Gapoh, he was enfeoffed as Lord Seongyeong. In the ninth month of Jeong-yu, he received the rank of Grand Defender of State. He took to wife the daughter of the Gentleman of Illustrious Virtue Seong, Left Commander and Joint Director of the Military—she was enfeoffed as Great Lady of the Three Han.

    This year, on the nineteenth day of the first month, illness took hold. Their Majesties, consumed with worry, spared no effort in prayer, medical care, and treatment. Upon his passing, they were struck with such profound grief that they abstained from food for two days. All the royal kinsmen, the hundred officials, and even the servants mourned without exception. The State Council, leading all the ministries, offered words of comfort and urged the taking of nourishment. On the following day, only rice gruel was permitted. Court audiences were suspended for three days. His Highness grieved so deeply that his body and spirit grew troubled. The elders and great ministers entreated him to take meat, but he refused. Their pleas repeated again and again, yet he remained unmoved, maintaining a plain diet for thirty days. The deceased was posthumously enfeoffed as Grand Prince and Duke of Byeon-Han, and granted the honorific title Sogyeong. The officials arranged the funeral rites, and on the day Eul-yu of the fourth month, he was laid to rest at the northeast slope of Sanni Valley in Goyang County. A shrine was erected at his former residence, and a heir was appointed to maintain his sacrifices. The burial and ritual observances were conducted without fault.

    I humbly reflect: Our sovereign, as a son, fulfills his filial duty to his father; as a father, he perfects his love for his children. In the funeral of Lord Seongyeong, his sincerity is profound and his grief boundless; his thoughts are deep and far-reaching, with all details scrupulously attended. Though this springs from his inherent virtue, it exemplifies the highest way of human relationships. Moreover, Lord Seongyeong possessed exceptional gifts and carried himself with integrity, thereby earning such profound royal affection. Truly was he noble! Yet fate granted him but a brief span. Alas, how can such sorrow be endured?

    I have long pondered the Analects, and lamented that even the sage Confucius could not escape weeping for his son Li who died before him. Now witnessing the passing of Sogyeong, I am convinced that heaven itself may harbor imperfection. With reverent bow and prostration, I compose this inscription:

    The Lord's essence—
    Clear as jade, warm as sunlight.
    His conduct—
    Filial, fraternal, gentle, and fair.
    Bright of mind, devoted to learning,
    Doubled was the affection of the royal pair.

    Why does heaven grant virtue
    Yet take away the span of years?
    O sovereign, most sacred,
    Your sorrow fills the heavens and earth.
    Is this not the work of what is imperfect?
    Who ordains such things?

    His rank was raised, his fief bestowed,
    An heir appointed to tend his sacred offerings.
    Sun and moon shine forth in brightness,
    Mountains and streams remain fair.
    His form lies deep in rest—
    May he dwell in peace eternal.
    Upon the tomb road stands this stone,
    And these characters inscribe our grief.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'The Nine Depths (九泉): A poetic reference to the underworld and the realm of the deceased in Chinese and Korean cosmology.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Eul-yu year: This refers to 1405 CE in the traditional East Asian calendar system.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Confucius wept for his son Li (鯉): A reference to the historical record that even the sage Confucius experienced profound grief at the death of his own son, illustrating the universality of human sorrow.'
